<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Buildings: Facets
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to add walls, doors, ladders, fences, cables, and gates to your buildings.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Overview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Facets are the building blocks of structures in Urban Chaos. Each facet type has unique
        properties and behaviors, but all share a common drawing workflow:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Select a building from the Buildings list</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click the appropriate facet icon (Add Wall, Add Ladder, etc.)</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Configure properties in the dialog that appears</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click <Bold>Draw on Map</Bold> to enter drawing mode</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>Click on the canvas to place facets, <Bold>right-click</Bold> to finish</Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Drawing Restriction:</Run>
                <Run>You cannot draw diagonally (except for cables). All walls, doors, ladders, fences, and gates must be axis-aligned — either horizontal or vertical on the grid. This is an engine limitation.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- WALLS -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Walls
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Walls are the most common facet type and appear <Bold Foreground="#90EE90">green</Bold>
        on the map. They form the primary structure of buildings and can be stacked, textured,
        and configured with various properties.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Adding Walls
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select a building from the Buildings list (create one first if needed).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click the <Bold>Add Wall icon</Bold> in the toolbar. The <Bold>Add Facets</Bold>
                window appears.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select the facet sub-type. For walls, there is only one option: <Bold>Normal</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Set the facet properties:
            </Paragraph>
            <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <Bold>Height</Bold> — Measured in quarter storeys (4 = 1 storey, 8 = 2 storeys)
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <Bold>Block Height</Bold> — Usually 4 (standard storey size)
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <Bold>Y Offset</Bold> — 0 for ground level, higher values to stack on existing structures
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <Bold>Style Index</Bold> — Texture pattern from
                        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">style.tma</Run>
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
                <ListItem>
                    <Paragraph>
                        <Bold>Flags</Bold> — Optional properties
                    </Paragraph>
                </ListItem>
            </List>
            <Paragraph Margin="16,4,0,0">
                <Run FontStyle="Italic" Foreground="#A0A0A0">
                    For detailed explanations of Height, Block Height, Y Offset, Style Index, and
                    Flags, see the</Run>
                <Bold Foreground="#7AD7FF">Buildings: Properties &amp; Flags</Bold>
                <Run FontStyle="Italic" Foreground="#A0A0A0">section.</Run>
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click <Bold>Draw on Map</Bold>. Your cursor changes to draw mode.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click once to set the start point, move to the desired end position, and click
                again to place the wall. The wall must be horizontal or vertical (no diagonals).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Repeat to add more walls. <Bold>Right-click</Bold> when finished drawing.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_add_wall.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Add Facets window for walls showing Type, Height, Block Height, Y Offset, Style Index, Flags, and texture preview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If you draw walls that form a closed polygon (a complete connected loop with no gaps),
        the Auto-Build system will detect it and automatically apply roof textures, set PAP flags,
        and create walkables (if enabled).
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Quick Resizing and Rotating Walls
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        After placing a wall, you can quickly resize or rotate it without recreating it:
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Margin="0,8,0,2">
        To Resize:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Click the facet</Bold> on the map canvas to select it. The facet is highlighted.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Green bulbs</Bold> appear at both endpoints of the facet.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Click and drag</Bold> one of the green bulbs to a new location on the grid.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Release the mouse button to commit the resize. The facet is now resized to the new length.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Margin="0,6,0,2">
        To Rotate in Place:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Click the facet</Bold> on the map canvas to select it. The facet is highlighted.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Press the <Bold>Space Bar</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The facet rotates 90 degrees clockwise around its center point, staying in place.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Press <Bold>Space Bar</Bold> multiple times to continue rotating (90°, 180°, 270°, back to 0°).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is much faster than deleting and redrawing a facet when you need to adjust its position
        or length.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- LADDERS -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Ladders
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Ladders allow the player to climb vertical surfaces and appear <Bold Foreground="#FFA500">orange</Bold>
        on the map. Unlike walls, ladders have only two configurable properties and are always
        <Bold>1 cell wide</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Adding Ladders
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select a building and click the <Bold>Add Ladder icon</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Set the <Bold>Height</Bold> (in quarter storeys) and <Bold>Y Offset</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click <Bold>Draw on Map</Bold> and place the ladder by clicking once, moving to
                the end position (1 cell away), and clicking again.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <Paragraph>
        When drawing a ladder, you will see a <Bold>direction arrow</Bold> indicating which way
        the ladder faces (inward or outward from the wall). If you make a mistake, press
        <Bold>Escape</Bold> to cancel the draw and start again.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_ladder.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Ladder (orange) placed on a wall with direction arrow showing ladder orientation
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- FENCES -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Fences
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Fences appear <Bold Foreground="#FFFF00">yellow</Bold> on the map and have the same
        properties as walls. Textures are managed via the <Bold>Style Index</Bold>. There are
        three fence sub-types:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Fence Flat</Bold> — A fence with no top barrier. Can be climbed over.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Fence</Bold> — A fence with a barbed wire top. Cannot be climbed over.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Fence Brick</Bold> — A flat-topped fence that cannot be climbed over (solid barrier).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Key Difference from Walls
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Unlike walls, fence textures are always <Bold>stretched</Bold> to the height of the
        facet rather than stacked vertically. This means a 2-storey fence will show one stretched
        texture tile, whereas a 2-storey wall will show two stacked texture tiles.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_fences.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Three fence types (yellow) - Fence Flat, Fence (barbed), Fence Brick - showing texture stretching
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- CABLES -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Cables
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Cables appear <Bold Foreground="#FF6347">red</Bold> on the map and are the <Bold>only
        facet type</Bold> that can be drawn diagonally. They are useful for overhead power lines,
        zip lines, and other suspended elements.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Adding Cables
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select a building and click the <Bold>Add Cable icon</Bold>. The <Bold>Add New Cable</Bold>
                window appears.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Set the <Bold>start point</Bold> (X, Z coordinates) and start <Bold>height</Bold>
                (in quarter storeys).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Set the <Bold>end point</Bold> (X, Z coordinates) and end <Bold>height</Bold>
                (in quarter storeys).
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Alternatively, click <Bold>Draw on Map</Bold> to manually place the start and end
                points directly on the canvas by clicking twice.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                The window automatically calculates the required number of segments and shows a
                <Bold>preview</Bold> of the cable path.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click <Bold>Create Cable</Bold> to place it on the map.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_cable.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Add New Cable dialog showing Start/End coordinates, heights, segment calculation, and preview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Example use case:</Bold> Create a cable from the roof of a building (height 8 QS)
        down to the ground (height 0 QS) to simulate a power line or zip line.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- DOORS -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Doors
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Doors appear <Bold Foreground="#DA70D6">purple</Bold> on the map and are portals between
        the outside view and the inside view. Doors behave differently depending on the building type:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,4,0,0" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>House buildings:</Bold> Doors function as <Bold>elevators</Bold>, teleporting
                the player to the top of the building.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Warehouse buildings:</Bold> Doors allow the player to enter the interior and
                walk around inside.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Door Requirements
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Doors are maximum <Bold>1 cell wide</Bold> (like ladders) and must be placed in a gap
        of <Bold>exactly 1 cell</Bold>. When a door seals a 1-cell gap in a wall polygon, it
        completes the closed polygon and triggers the Auto-Build system (if enabled).
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        When drawing, a <Bold>direction arrow</Bold> shows the correct orientation. The arrow
        should face <Bold>outside</Bold> so the player can approach and enter through the door.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9ECBFF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Adding Doors
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,6,0,6" Foreground="#E0E0E0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Select a building (typically a warehouse) and click the <Bold>Add Door icon</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Set the <Bold>Y Offset</Bold>. Use 0 for ground level, or a higher value if the
                door accesses an upper floor.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                Click <Bold>Draw on Map</Bold> and place the door in a 1-cell gap between walls.
                Ensure the arrow points <Bold>outward</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_door.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Door (purple) placed in a 1-cell gap with direction arrow pointing outward
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,4,0,0">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Warehouse Door Best Practices:</Run>
                <LineBreak/>
                <LineBreak/>
                <Run>• Leave a 1-cell gap in the wall polygon before placing the door. The door will seal the gap and complete the closed polygon.</Run>
                <LineBreak/>
                <LineBreak/>
                <Run>• Do not make the first layer of a warehouse building multi-storey. Doors cannot span multiple storeys, so the polygon will not close properly and the Auto-Build system will not trigger.</Run>
                <LineBreak/>
                <LineBreak/>
                <Run>• Instead, build the first layer at exactly 4 quarter storeys (1 storey) so the door fits. If you need additional height, create a separate facet group offset by 4 quarter storeys and stack it on top.</Run>
                <LineBreak/>
                <LineBreak/>
                <Run>• If you forget the gap and draw a completely closed wall loop, you can still add a door — but it will be covered by the wall texture and won't function correctly. Always leave the 1-cell gap first.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- GATES -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Gates
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Gates appear <Bold Foreground="#87CEEB">blue</Bold> on the map and function similarly
        to fences. They are styled via the <Bold>Style Index</Bold> and have the same properties
        as walls (Height, Block Height, Y Offset, Flags).
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The key difference from fences is that gates can be <Bold>programmed to open</Bold> via
        mission files during gameplay. The <Bold>Open</Bold> flag is set at runtime by the mission
        script, allowing the gate to swing open when triggered by an event or player action.
    </Paragraph>
    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,4">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMapEditor;component/Help/Images/buildings_gate.png"
               MaxWidth="700" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#888888" FontSize="11" FontStyle="Italic" Margin="0,0,0,8" TextAlignment="Center">
        Screenshot: Gate (blue) placed as part of a fence line, can be opened via mission scripts
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Quick Reference
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Summary of facet types and their characteristics:
    </Paragraph>
